                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-206-off1057 t18280911-206-victim1189"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , and fixed to a certain building of his
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-206-person1190">
                  JOHN 
                  WALKER
               <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1190" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1190" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1190" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am agent to Mr. Thomas Dunstan - he has a house in <placeName id="t18280911-206-crimeloc1059">Pleasant-row, Mile-and Old-town, Stepney</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-206-crimeloc1059" type="placeName" value="Pleasant-row, Mile-and Old-town, Stepney"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-206-crimeloc1059" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-206-off1057 t18280911-206-crimeloc1059"></join>; I was at that house on Tuesday, the 26th of August - it had been lately repaired, and was unoccupied; I afterwards received information, and went there - I found the sashes broken, the glass gone, and the locks gone off three doors; I did not find any of the articles - they had been previously taken care of; the glass was worth 1s. 6d. a square.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-206-person1191">
                  GEORGE 
                  MASSEY
               <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1191" type="surname" value="MASSEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1191" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1191" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman of Mile-end Oldtown. I was on duty in Pleasant-row on the 28th of August; at four o'clock in the morning I went up to the prosecutor's house, and saw a piece of flannel in the keyhole - I pushed it through, and then missed the lock; I called the other watchman, and he came - I had seen the place all right at three o'clock - the other watchman came, with a lamp-lighter, who put his ladder up and opened the window; he said, "There are thieves in the back part" - I went round, and found the prisoner and another man coming over the back fence; I sprung my rattle, and sung out, Stop thief! the prisoner was taken by a man going to his labour - I followed him, and had kept him in sight, oxcept just as he turned the corner; I took him to the watch-house, and found this chisel on him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-206-person1192">
                  JAMES 
                  FULLER
               <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1192" type="surname" value="FULLER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1192" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1192" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I heard a watchman's rattle on the 28th of August, opened the window and looked out; I saw the prisoner running, and Massey caught hold of him - I saw the prisoner throw something from his pocket.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I do not suppose that witness saw me throw anything away. Witness. Yes, I did, and my brother went and picked them up - it was those two screws.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-206-person1193">
                  ROBERT 
                  CHRISTIAN
               <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1193" type="surname" value="CHRISTIAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1193" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-person1193" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 28th of August the prisoner was brought to the watch-house - I searched him, and found some matches and a short pipe on him; I went to the house, and found twenty-two squares of glass in the back room, and four sashes broken to pieces; I found the lock of the street door broken. and lying in the passage - it had been broken evidently by force from the outside - I received these two screws from Fuller; I compared them with the holes in the door where the lock had been taken off, and they fitted exactly.</p>
               <p>MR. WALKER. The key of the street door lock was in my possession, and is here now.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was going to my work about half-past four o'clock that morning, when I was stopped by a man, and they took me.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-206-verdict1060" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-206-verdict1060" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 20.</p>
